{"key":"post-16286727","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16286727</id>\n<content>When making a casing layer, I prefer to use a tiny amount of hydrated lime over a much larger amount of calcium carbonate.&amp;nbsp; The reason is the hydrated lime will swing the pH up much faster, which helps to prevent mold spores from germinating.&amp;nbsp; You don't want lime in substrates because mushroom mycelium(as does mold) prefers a slightly acidic media.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Use agricultural gypsum.&amp;nbsp; Many growers shred drywall, and indeed some brands of agricultural gypsum are obviously made from shredded drywall scraps because I've pulled pieces of white and gray paper from them.&amp;nbsp; Don't use plaster of paris unless you're going to prepare it per the instructions and then after it sets, grind it back down to a powder for use.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Just a note here:&amp;nbsp; If you're buying calcium carbonate, don't get food grade from a brewing supply because it's not needed for mushroom growing.&amp;nbsp; You should be able to get it for a fraction of the price you paid.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16286772</next>\n<prev>16286701</prev>\n<first>16286701</first>\n<last>16291368</last>\n<when>1338035736</when>\n<utime>05/26/12 03:35 PM</utime>\n</post>"}